Location: Forêt de Fontainebleau (near  Fontainebleau), Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France
Remarks:
That's a  faint, rare and special call in decrescendo, uttered by male at the beggining of the breeding period, generally when the female is arrived. At this period, when females are choosing (or not) nest cavities selected before by  males, male can uttered, specially when it's close to a female, varied and sometimes strange calls. This call in decrescendo is one of them. That's a kind of "nuptial" call. When you hear it, you can be sure a female is present. (Because in this species the males arrive before females, and choose the nest cavities. And after they are waiting for a female, trying to attract her to show the nest cavitie. If the female chooses the nest cavitie, she chooses the male!)

Location: Forêt de Fontainebleau (near  Fontainebleau), Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France
Remarks:
This is a rare call I have just recorded two or three times in 9 years . Always uttered from the ground, it's constitued by a serie of ascending and then descending notes. And beteween those notes, the bird utters the traditionnal "si" territorial call. Always uttered at the begining of the breeding season, perhaps during the nest construction, it could be a kind of copulating incitement. See also XC146356.
